# Vercel: one production deploy per commit

**Production host:** https://www.mesaskyeview.com (project `mesaskyeview-com`, team `janet-duffys-projects`)

## Cause of duplicate deployments

Each `git push` to `main` already triggers **one** production build via the Vercel GitHub integration (`github/DrJanDuffy` in the dashboard).

Running **`vercel --prod`** or **`pnpm run vercel:prod`** after a push triggers a **second** production build (`actor: cursor-cli`, `drjanduffy` avatar). Same commit SHA, double build minutes, confusing dashboard.

## Required behavior for agents and humans

1. After **`git push origin main`**, **do not** run `vercel --prod`, `vercel deploy --prod`, or `pnpm run vercel:prod`.
2. Wait for the Git-connected deployment to finish (Vercel dashboard or `vercel ls mesaskyeview-com`).
3. Use CLI production deploy **only** when Git deploy is unavailable (emergency hotfix without push, or project not linked to Git).

## Preview deployments — disabled

- **`vercel.json`** sets `git.deploymentEnabled` so only **`main`** deploys. PR/branch pushes do not create Vercel previews.
- **`.github/workflows/vercel-preview.yml`** is manual-only (`workflow_dispatch`); it does not run on pull requests.
- **Live site:** https://www.mesaskyeview.com — never treat `*.vercel.app` preview URLs as production.
- In Vercel dashboard (optional belt-and-suspenders): **Settings → Git → Ignored Build Step → Only build production**.

## Never stack CLI on Git production

- After **`git push origin main`**, do not run `vercel --prod` or `pnpm run vercel:prod`.

## Cloudflare

DNS/cache only (gray cloud). Production app is Vercel—not `cloudflare-deploy.yml` on push unless explicitly requested via workflow_dispatch.
